issue.title: Compliance with the XDG Base Directory Specification

labels.name: type:feature
labels.description: The user is asking for a new feature.

issue.body:
Currently, Keras puts all of its configuration files and models into ~/.keras directory on Linux. This clutters up the user's home directory.

Keras could instead put its configuration files to XDG_CONFIG_HOME/keras/ and models to XDG_DATA_HOME/keras/models/.

It would be great if Keras used the standard directories, at least on Linux.

- [x] Check that you are up-to-date with the master branch of Keras. You can update with:
pip install git+git://github.com/keras-team/keras.git --upgrade --no-deps

- [x] If running on TensorFlow, check that you are up-to-date with the latest version. The installation instructions can be found [here](https://www.tensorflow.org/get_started/os_setup).

- [x] If running on Theano, check that you are up-to-date with the master branch of Theano. You can update with:
pip install git+git://github.com/Theano/Theano.git --upgrade --no-deps

- [x] Provide a link to a GitHub Gist of a Python script that can reproduce your issue (or just copy the script here if it is short).

comment.body: I should not have to manually set env vars so that programs respect the XDG base directory specification... it's there for a reason, can you imagine your home directory if all developers just put their files wherever they wanted?

comment.body:
Hi @AakashKumarNain 
I'm not sure if I understand your question correctly.

We need the extra `cast` because `tfnp.log*` will accidentally upcast the tensor from bfloat16 to float64. This behavior happens ONLY at bfloat16.

All the other backends will maintain the original dtype.

```python
import jax.numpy as jnp
import numpy as np
import torch
import tensorflow as tf


tfnp = tf.experimental.numpy
tfnp.experimental_enable_numpy_behavior()

# jax
x = jnp.array(10, dtype="bfloat16")
y = jnp.log(x)
print(y, y.dtype)

# tensorflow
x = tf.constant(10, dtype="bfloat16")
y = tfnp.log(x)
print(y, y.dtype)

# torch
x = torch.tensor(10, dtype=torch.bfloat16)
y = torch.log(x)
print(y, y.dtype)

# np (using higher precision for checking)
x = np.array(10, dtype="float32")
y = np.log(x)
print(y)

```

```bash
2.29688 bfloat16
tf.Tensor(2.302585092994046, shape=(), dtype=float64) <dtype: 'float64'>
tensor(2.2969, dtype=torch.bfloat16) torch.bfloat16
2.3025851

# we can see that tensorflow has a more accurate output compared to jax and torch
# but we need to cast the output to the original dtype
```

pull_request.title: Apply `backend.result_type` to `linspace`, `logspace` and `log*`
pull_request.body:
The dtype promotion and compatibility rules might be as follows:
- Match the dtype inference from JAX.
- When an integer input becomes a floating-point output, use `backend.floatx()` for the best attempt.
- Make the best effort to support all dtypes for all operators in all backends (although this might introduce some overhead for checking).

Additionally, this PR fix the dtype inference of `sqrt`. We should promote to `backend.floatx()` instead of float64 when the input dtype is int64.

issue.title: Add `GCViT` Implementation as Multi-backend Example
issue.body:
I wrote this [notebook](https://www.kaggle.com/code/awsaf49/gcvit-global-context-vision-transformer/notebook) last year, which implements the [GCViT: Global Context Vision Transformer](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2206.09959.pdf) (ICML 2023) paper from scratch along with a port of the official ImageNet weights. I believe it would be beneficial to include this work as an example on `keas.io` with `multi-backend` feature.

Currently, this work supports `TensorFlow`, but I can adapt it for `multi-backend` support. The notebook might be somewhat lengthy, but I can condense it if required.

issue.title: Torch dynamo `Could not infer dtype of NoneType`
issue.body:
Do to some recent changes to the torch backend (I think we enabled compilation by default?), a simple torch `fit()` call with dict inputs will fail.

https://colab.research.google.com/gist/mattdangerw/5f966e9a35667396819efe13d0fa6980/torch-error.ipynb

The direct error is `Could not infer dtype of NoneType`, but the stack trace makes it look like the `dm-tree` library is involved.

comment.body:
I’m on PTO so would have to take a deeper look when I get back next Monday but from the stack trace this looks like a tracing error. 

With dynamo, tracing can be a bit contextual so depending on the combination of keras APIs called (in specific order) and the type, dtype, and shape of the inputs and intermediaries, it could lead to tracing errors, guard failures (and therefore graph breaks) or legitimate graph breaks. There isn’t a great way to absolutely, 100% always guarantee that all keras usages be dynamo compatible. That’s why with jit_compile=“auto” (the default for keras trainers) we run with eager for the pytorch backend and only run with dynamo if the user wants to see if their particular usage will see speed ups with dynamo. 

This is in part due to the way dynamo is designed. PyTorch’s intention is basically follow this path:

1. run with eager for maximum compatibility (basically everything works pretty well on eager with ok performance)
2. try dynamo, if it works out of the box great. 
3. Otherwise you put in the effort to make your code compatible with dynamo. Presumably the more effort you put to remove graph breaks and such, the better perf you’ll get. But ultimately it’s up to you to decide how much effort you want to put into it. 

This is fundamentally different from how JAX works since it’s basically all or nothing with JAX. If it runs then you can leave it up to XLA to give you the “best perf” but you need to make it compatible for even the first run to execute.

commits.message:
Add support for Tensorflow SparseTensors: optimizers. (#18692)

All optimizers now handle sparse gradients in the form of `tf.IndexedSlices`.
Where applicable, this results in partial updates of variables using `scatter_add`/`scatter_sub`.

This was done by performing the following changes in optimizers code:
- replacing all negative operations (e.g. `+`) with the equivalent Keras op (e.g. `ops.add`). Note that an exception was made for scalars.
- replacing `variable.assign/assign_add/assign_sub` by `self.assign/assign_add/assign_sub`.

commits.message:
Fix tracking of special characters in the progress bar. (#18687)

Currently, if `prog_width == 0`, we do not track the 8 special characters in `bar`, causing the progress logs to "jump" a few lines above.

The condition `prog_width == 0` does happen, if an epoch has enough batches.

pull_request.title: Add devcontainer for easier external contribution
pull_request.body:
With this PR, the codespaces (or vscode) would start with all the linting and formatting set up, and all the dependencies installed.

Makes it easier for contributors to contribute code.

issue.title: Torch dynamo `Could not infer dtype of NoneType`
issue.body:
Do to some recent changes to the torch backend (I think we enabled compilation by default?), a simple torch `fit()` call with dict inputs will fail.

https://colab.research.google.com/gist/mattdangerw/5f966e9a35667396819efe13d0fa6980/torch-error.ipynb

The direct error is `Could not infer dtype of NoneType`, but the stack trace makes it look like the `dm-tree` library is involved.

comment.body:
I think the basic use case should be jit_compile=“auto” since it would default to the most natural run-mode for each framework (jit compiled mode for tf and jax and eager for torch)

The dm_tree issue isn’t exactly what is causing the exception, rather it is causing graph-breaks (does not manifest as python errors) and therefore leads to poor performance as graph breaks runs in python-land and therefore loses out on compiler optimization opportunities.
